Arroyo Valley Trail (Santa Rita Road to I-680)
Observation Details: On one location a large group of 5 birds are feeding on Blue Elder berries, there are young birds in the mix.  In another location I find a tree nest cavity 3 Western Bluebirds are going in and out of it. There are at least two young hopping in and out of the nest cavity as if they were practicing venturing about, they don't go far, just on the branches around the nest and hop back in. I did some reading and apparently fledglings once they leave the nest stay in hiding and get fed by parents and don't return to the nest. Apparently it is too hard for them to balance on the opening of the nest cavity.  If so, it wasn't the case for these birds. I am not sure how old those birds were, probably not fledglings, but certainly not adults yet,  maybe old enough to feed themselves and the cavity was only a roosting place (even though it was quite early in the afternoon for roosting). I am not sure what to think of it. At some point, a nonchalant Nuttall’s Woodpecker got too close and one Western Bluebirds chased it away.

A juvenile western bluebird flew by us and landed in one of the deciduous trees in front of the library. It remained there and allowed us to approach quite closely to see the sharply-contrasting streaking on its breast. Katherine noticed that it had a bluish cast to the feathering on its back as well. As we walked on across the lawn towards the school building, it flew in close and landed on the grass only about eight feet away from us, remaining there only a short time before returning to its perch in the tree.

The last remaining nestling (of four original nestlings) finally fledged this morning. Does seem to have a foot problem (either nesting material or some sort of growth on its feet, and missing front talons), but it seems to move around ok.   The parents started feeding young four weeks ago, so this nestling has been in the box for a *very* long time; it stayed there for more than a week after the last nestling fledged (and subsequently drowned). We're pleasantly surprised that he even managed to fledge successfully. Spent the day on the pool deck and made friends with some House Sparrow fledglings. Parents remain very attentive

Observation Details: Looking for the reported Mountain Bluebird but cannot say we found it. But this discovery was an interesting one.  One photo shows a a bird with a rufous toned back. The other photo a bird with a drabbish gray back. I first thought one bird must have perched, then flew, then a second  bird flew in and perched in the same spot. But  looking at the lichen on the wire, the lichen changes color too! The photos here, I believe,  are of the same bird. And this may be as a result of how my camera processes color based on light and background.
